WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.640
Perfect. All right. So the idea of MRD-directed therapy, right, is you don't need to wait for a morphologic overt relapse.

00:00:12.640 --> 00:00:27.820
If you can identify reliably, you know, persistent or progressing residual disease, you know, can you intervene early and then prevent the toxicity, you know, of patients who are getting therapy when they, you know, are cytopenic and have neutropenic infections,

00:00:28.420 --> 00:00:32.940
as well as easier efficacy, right, because there's less burden of disease there.

00:00:33.020 --> 00:00:36.480
And we talked already, you know, in the last session about various different MRD markers.

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:50.020
You know, some patients can have that reliable NPM1 or FLT3 FLT3 core binding factor KMT2A, but in many cases, we don't have a great specific MRD molecular or genomic base.

00:00:50.120 --> 00:00:55.960
And so flow MRD becomes the kind of overarching currently what we're using, although in the future, I think that will change.

00:00:56.840 --> 00:01:01.140
And just as, you know, as a background, so NPM1 is the perfect example, right?

00:01:01.160 --> 00:01:13.720
We know in newly diagnosed NPM1 mutated patients who are in a remission, in their first remission, you know, if they become MRD negative, they have a good chance of being cured and we don't need to proceed to a transplant.

00:01:13.820 --> 00:01:24.020
Whereas even though we say NPM1 is favorable, if they stay MRD positive, you can see that first curve, they're not doing that great, and having a transplant in first remission really improves the outcome.

00:01:24.020 --> 00:01:26.720
So this is kind of an example of how MRD really.

00:01:26.840 --> 00:01:28.040
Is impactful.

00:01:29.100 --> 00:01:35.420
So the intercept study, it stands for investigating novel therapy to target early relapse and clonal evolution preemptively.

00:01:36.040 --> 00:01:39.320
This is really the brainchild of Andrew Way and others in Australia.

00:01:39.860 --> 00:01:48.820
And we are participating at MD Anderson as the one kind of US site in this otherwise Australian study, where you take AML in first or second remission.

00:01:48.820 --> 00:01:56.720
They are enrolled into this master consent where you're monitoring MRD and at the time of failure, whether it's MRD failure or.

00:01:56.840 --> 00:02:07.500
Mere morphologic relapse, which up to 15% blasts, you're then allocated to an arm based on your genomics, with the various different treatment arms shown here.

00:02:07.500 --> 00:02:17.780
The objective, kind of generally, is to see if we can produce an improvement in MRD response rate of 40% or higher.

00:02:17.780 --> 00:02:22.200
Certainly many other secondary objectives and just kind of drilling down a little bit more.

00:02:22.200 --> 00:02:26.160
You know, an MRD response is defined as someone who has detectable MMR.

00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:26.660
Right.

00:02:26.660 --> 00:02:38.140
If you have detectable MRD, you get one log or better reduction or flow less than 0.1% within 100 days of starting this intercept directed study therapy based on the arm you're on.

00:02:38.140 --> 00:02:49.640
We're, of course, looking at clinical endpoints of relapse free survival, how long it takes, duration of MRD response, as well as many other and a fun translational analysis being done on the samples of these patients.

00:02:51.560 --> 00:02:53.400
Treatment is for 12 cycles.

00:02:53.400 --> 00:02:56.480
So this was a big, you know, contentious discussion back and forth, you know.

00:02:56.480 --> 00:03:01.680
This is a trial, but also, you know, how long, you know, similar to the conversations we've been having earlier today.

00:03:02.420 --> 00:03:08.840
In patients who are doing well after 12 cycles that are not transitioning to transplant, there is the option to continue further.

00:03:09.640 --> 00:03:15.780
And patients are followed for up to 24 months where you're getting these time points and getting these samples to the lab.

